  "text": "Finally we turn to the single pole as z 1 approaches z 2 . There are three ways to get a first order pole. In the first two ways, 1 and 2 are in the same pair, and terms in the product ofχ's give (z 1 − z 2 ) 2 which then combines with the 1/(z 1 − z 2 ) 3 term in Eq. 13 to give a single pole. One way to get such a quadratic term is by expanding terms of the form (here we use shorthand notation [CITATION_1] 23)(24)(25)(26) + . . .",
